  "nursesNote": "Antihypertensives lower blood pressure to prevent complications. Beta-blockers (metoprolol) lower heart rate and blood pressure, so the nurse checks the apical pulse and blood pressure first and holds the dose for a pulse under 60 or low blood pressure; they are not stopped abruptly (rebound) and can mask low-blood-sugar signs. ACE inhibitors (lisinopril) can cause a dry cough and raise potassium; facial or throat swelling (angioedema) is an emergency requiring the drug to be stopped. ARBs (losartan) are similar with less cough. Calcium channel blockers (amlodipine) can cause ankle edema, and grapefruit juice is avoided. For all of these, the patient rises slowly to prevent orthostatic dizziness, keeps taking the medication even when feeling well, and monitors blood pressure at home.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Check apical pulse and BP before a beta-blocker; hold if pulse under 60",
    "Do not stop beta-blockers abruptly",
    "Monitor for ACE inhibitor dry cough and high potassium",
    "Treat angioedema as an emergency and stop the drug",
    "Teach rising slowly and continued adherence with home BP checks"
  ],
